'''State Route&nbsp;503''' (SR&nbsp;503) is a {{convert|54.11|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[State highways in Washington|state highway]] serving [[Clark County, Washington|Clark]] and [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz]] counties in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. The highway travels north from a short [[Concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with [[Washington State Route 500|SR&nbsp;500]] in [[Orchards, Washington|Orchards]] through [[Battle Ground, Washington|Battle Ground]], the eastern terminus of [[Washington State Route 502|SR&nbsp;502]], and communities in rural Clark County before crossing the [[Lewis River (Washington)|Lewis River]] on the [[Yale Bridge]]. SR&nbsp;503 intersects its [[Washington State Route 503 Spur|spur route]] and turns west to parallel the Lewis River downstream to [[Woodland, Washington|Woodland]], where the highway ends at an interchange with [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate&nbsp;5]] (I-5). The highway was part of the [[Lewis River Road]], signed as [[State Road 15 (Washington 1909-1919)|State Road&nbsp;15]], from 1909 until 1919. The current route of SR&nbsp;503 was split between Secondary State Highway&nbsp;1S (SSH&nbsp;1) from Woodland to Battle Ground and SSH&nbsp;1U from Battle Ground to Orchard in 1937, combined to form SR&nbsp;503 during the [[1964 highway renumbering (Washington)|1964 highway renumbering]]. A spur route, established in 1991, travels northeast into the [[Gifford Pinchot National Forest]] along [[Yale Lake]], serving the community of [[Cougar, Washington|Cougar]].

==Route description==
[[File:Yale Bridge WA1.jpg|thumb|left|SR&nbsp;503 crossing the [[Lewis River (Washington)|Lewis River]] on the [[Yale Bridge]] between [[Clark County, Washington|Clark]] and [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz]] counties.]]

SR&nbsp;503 begins [[Concurrency (road)|concurrent]] to [[Washington State Route 500|SR&nbsp;500]] at an intersection with Fourth Plain Road in [[Orchards, Washington|Orchards]].
<ref name="gnis-orchards">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Orchards |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1512536 |work=[[Geographic Names Information System]] |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The two highways travel north on the four-lane 117th Avenue through Orchards until SR&nbsp;500 turns east onto Padden Parkway, while SR&nbsp;503 continues north into rural [[Clark County, Washington|Clark County]], passing [[Prairie High School (Vancouver, Washington)|Prairie High School]] and [[Mountain View High School (Washington)|Mountain View High School]].<ref name="gnis-prairie">{{citation |date=March 1, 1993 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Prairie High School |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1515231 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-mtnview">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Mountain View High School |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1515236 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The roadway bypasses [[Brush Prairie, Washington|Brush Prairie]] on its west side and crosses a the [[Chelatchie Prairie Railroad]], before it turns northeast onto 122nd Avenue.<ref name="gnis-brush">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Brush Prairie |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1512040 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="rail-2012">{{cite map |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |title=2011 Washington State Rail System |date=January 2012 |url=http://wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/FDBE2AB4-E504-4AC5-9E30-6A2CC4FAAD34/0/2011Ownership.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503 enters [[Battle Ground, Washington|Battle Ground]] as 10th Avenue and intersects the eastern terminus of [[Washington State Route 502|SR&nbsp;502]] west of [[Battle Ground High School]].<ref name="gnis-battleground">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Battle Ground |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1530801 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="int-502">{{citation |date=December 31, 1992 |title=SR 502: Junction SR 503 |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |url=http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/mapsdata/tools/InterchangeViewer/pdf/SR502/502X007.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-bghs">{{citation |date=May 1, 1992 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Battle Ground High School |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1514117 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The highway crosses the East Fork of the [[Lewis River (Washington)|Lewis River]] and leaves Battle Ground to pass [[Lewisville Park]], listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] and located in [[Lewisville, Washington|Lewisville]].<ref name="nrhp-bridge">{{citation |date=June 6, 1986 |title=National Register of Historic Places: Weekly List of Actions |publisher=[[United States Department of the Interior]], [[National Park Service]] |url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/Weekly_Register_List_1986.pdf |page=70 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-lewisville">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Lewisville Park |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1510717 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-eastfork">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: East Fork Lewis River |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1519109 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503 continues heading northeast into a heavily forested region of the [[Cascades Range|Cascades foothills]], toward [[Fargher Lake]] and [[Amboy, Washington|Amboy]].<ref name="google">{{google maps |title=State Route 503 |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=NE+117th+Ave&daddr=45.9507715,-122.3662139+to:Lewis+River+Rd&hl=en&ll=45.779975,-122.634888&spn=0.512394,1.352692&sll=45.782595,-122.647845&sspn=0.512368,1.352692&geocode=FaDTuAIdS_-x-A%3BFTMnvQId-9a0-CnTfbyYFjKUVDG43W3DE9TyxQ%3BFbh1vAIdZxav-A&mra=dpe&mrsp=1&sz=10&via=1&t=m&z=10 |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>

SR&nbsp;503 turns east onto Fargher Lake Highway at Rock Creek and enters Amboy by following [[Chelatchie Creek]] towards [[Yale Lake]].<ref name="gnis-rock">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Rock |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1525109 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-chelatchie">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Chelatchie Creek |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1517653 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-yalelake">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Yale Lake |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1528347 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The highway travels north and crosses the Lewis River into [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]] on the {{convert|532|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} [[Yale Bridge]].<ref name="haer-bridge">{{citation |last=Soderberg |first=Lisa |title=HAER Inventory: Yale Bridge |date=August 1979 |publisher=[[Historic American Engineering Record]] |url=https://fortress.wa.gov/dahp/wisaard/documents/RN/0/0/541.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> The one-lane [[warren truss]] bridge, listed on the National Register of Historic Places,<ref name="nrhp-bridge">{{citation |date=March 1, 1983 |title=National Register of Historic Places; Annual Listing of Historic Properties |publisher=United States Department of the Interior, National Park Service |url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/Weekly_List_FR-March-1-1983-listingyear1982.pdf |page=44 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> is located downstream from the [[Yale Dam]] on Yale Lake and upstream of [[Lake Merwin]].<ref name="gnis-yaledam">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Yale Dam |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1528346 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-merwin">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Lake Merwin |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1523015 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503 continues into Cowlitz County and turns west onto Lewis River Road at an intersection with its [[Washington State Route 503 Spur|spur route]] that heads east to [[Skamania County, Washington|Skamania County]]. The highway travels southwestward in the Lewis River valley and passes through the communities of [[Yale, Washington|Yale]] and [[Ariel, Washington|Ariel]].<ref name="gnis-yale">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Yale |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1528345 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-ariel">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Ariel |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:3198340354266946::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1510787 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503 enters [[Woodland, Washington|Woodland]] and turns south onto Goerig Street before ending at a [[diamond interchange]] with [[Interstate 5 in Washington|I-5]] near the [[confluence]] of the Lewis and [[Columbia River|Columbia]] rivers.<ref name="log"/><ref name="google"/><ref name="int-5">{{citation |date=September 29, 2011 |title=SR 5 - Exit 21: Junction SR 503/Lewis River Drive |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |url=http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/mapsdata/tools/InterchangeViewer/pdf/SR005/005X021.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>

Every year, the [[Washington State Department of Transportation]] (WSDOT) conducts a series of surveys on its highways in the state to measure traffic volume. This is expressed in terms of [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT), which is a measure of traffic volume for any average day of the year. In 2011, WSDOT calculated that the busiest section of the highway was the SR&nbsp;500 concurrency in Orchards, serving 34,000 vehicles, while the least busiest section was at the western terminus of SR&nbsp;503&nbsp;Spur east of Yale, serving 720 vehicles.<ref name="ATR">{{citation |author=Staff |year=2011 |title=2011 Annual Traffic Report |publisher=Washington State Department of Transportation |url=http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/mapsdata/travel/pdf/Annual_Traffic_Report_2011.pdf |format=PDF |pages=185&ndash;187 |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503 between Orchards and Battle Ground is designated as part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name="NHS">{{cite map |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]] |title=National Highway System: Portland, OR--WA |url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/oregon/portland_or.pdf |date=October 1, 2012 |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> which includes roadways important to the national economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name="NHS-about">{{citation |title=What is the National Highway System? |url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/ |publisher=Federal Highway Administration |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>
{{clear}}
==History==
[[File:WA-503 Spur approaching western terminus.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Washington State Route 503 Spur|spur route]] of SR&nbsp;503, part of the original [[Lewis River Road]] in 1909, approaching its junction with the main highway near [[Yale, Washington|Yale]]]]

SR&nbsp;503 follows the route of [[State Road 15 (Washington 1909-1919)|State Road&nbsp;15]], established in 1909 as the [[Lewis River Road]], traveling east from [[Woodland, Washington|Woodland]] to the [[Skamania County, Washington|Skamania]] county line in [[Columbia National Forest]].<ref name="law1909">{{citation |author=Washington State Legislature |title=Session Laws of the State of Washington |edition=1909 |series=Session Laws of the State of Washington |date=March 6, 1909 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Cso4AAAAIAAJ |publisher=Washington State Legislature |location=[[Olympia, Washington]] |chapter=Chapter 61: Establishing State Roads |page=112 |quote=State Road No. 15, or the Lewis River road, beginning at Woodland in Cowlitz County and running thence up the north bank of Lewis river, following as nearly as practicable the county road, and continuing to the mouth of the Big Muddy, a tributary of Lewis river in Skamania county.}}</ref><ref name="usgs-1919">{{cite map |publisher=United States Geological Survey |title=Washington: Mt. St. Helens Quadrangle |year=1919 |url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/topo/washington/txu-pclmaps-topo-wa-mount_saint_helens-1916.jpg |scale=1:250,000 |format=JPG |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> The Lewis River Road was removed from the state highway system in 1919 and transferred to [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]] for maintenance.<ref name="law1919">{{citation |author=Washington State Legislature |title=Session Laws of the State of Washington |edition=1919 |series=Session Laws of the State of Washington |date=March 14, 1919 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=t704AAAAIAAJ |publisher=Washington State Legislature |location=Olympia, Washington |chapter=Chapter 110: Amending Highway Classification Act |page=239 |quote=State Road No. 10; Section 5901-j, Rem. & Bal. Code, establishing State Road No. 19; Section 5903, Rem. & Bal. Code, establishing State Roads Nos. 14, 15, 16 and 17, and that paragraph of Section 5905, Rem. & Bal. Code establishing State Road No. 7 and extensions, be and the same are hereby repealed.}}</ref> [[Clark County, Washington|Clark]] and Cowlitz counties contracted the [[Portland Bridge and Iron Company]] to build a bridge over the [[Lewis River (Washington)|Lewis River]] in 1917 and the bridge was opened to traffic in September 1920 at a cost of $15,000.<ref name="haer-bridge2">{{citation |last=Hadlow |first=Robert W. |title=Yale Bridge (Lewis River Bridge) - HAER No. WA-87: Written Historical and Descriptive Data |date=August 1993 |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/pnp/habshaer/wa/wa0400/wa0439/data/wa0439data.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Historic American Engineering Record |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> After the completion of the [[Merwin Dam]] downstream in 1931 caused water levels on the Lewis River to rise,<ref name="npdp-merwin">{{citation |author=National Performance of Dams Program |title=NPDP Directory: Merwin Dam (WA00149) |url=http://ce-npdp-serv2.stanford.edu/DamDirectory/DamDetail.jsp?npdp_id=WA00149 |publisher=[[Stanford University]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> the two counties completed a one-lane [[warren truss]] bridge named the [[Yale Bridge]] over the Lewis River the following year to serve the remote communities of [[Yale, Washington|Yale]] and [[Yacolt, Washington|Yacolt]].<ref name="haer-bridge"/><ref name="HL-bridge">{{citation |last=Long |first=Priscilla |date=March 14, 2003 |title=Clark and Cowlitz counties erect Yale Bridge across Lewis River in 1932. |url=http://www.washington.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&File_Id=5417 |work=[[HistoryLink]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> During the creation of the [[Primary State Highways (Washington)|primary and secondary state highways]] in 1937, State Road&nbsp;15 was added back to the state highway system as part of SSH&nbsp;1S, which traveled {{convert|57.60|mi|km|2}} from [[Primary State Highway 1 (Washington)|Primary State Highway&nbsp;1]] (PSH&nbsp;1) and [[U.S. Route 99|U.S. Route&nbsp;99]] (US&nbsp;99) to SSH&nbsp;1U in [[Battle Ground, Washington|Battle Ground]] and turned west to end at PSH&nbsp;1 and US&nbsp;99 north of [[Mount Vista, Washington|Mount Vista]].<ref name="law1937">{{citation |author=Washington State Legislature |title=Session Laws of the State of Washington |edition=1937 |series=Session Laws of the State of Washington |date=March 18, 1937 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=dcQ4AAAAIAAJ |publisher=Washington State Legislature |location=Olympia, Washington |chapter=Chapter 207: Classification of Public Highways |page=997 |quote=(r) Secondary State Highway No. 1S; beginning at a junction with Primary State Highway No. 1 in the vicinity north of Woodland, thence in an easterly direction by the most feasible route to Amboy, thence in a southerly direction by the most feasible route to Battleground, thence in a westerly direction by the most feasible route to a junction with Primary State Highway No. 1 in the vicinity north of Vancouver; (t) Secondary State Highway No. 1U; beginning at Battleground on Secondary State Highway No. 1S, thence in a southerly direction by the most feasible route to Orchard on the Secondary State Highway No. 8A.}}</ref><ref name="ATR-1960">{{citation |author=Staff |year=1960 |title=Annual Traffic Report, 1960 |publisher=[[Washington State Highway Commission]], [[Department of Highways (Washington)|Department of Highways]] |url=http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/mapsdata/travel/pdf/1960_ATR.pdf |format=PDF |pages=160&ndash;161 |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> PSH&nbsp;1U, also established in 1937, traveled {{convert|8.56|mi|km|2}} south from SSH&nbsp;1S in Battle Ground to [[Secondary State Highway 8A (Washington)|SSH&nbsp;8A]] in [[Orchards, Washington|Orchards]].<ref name="law1937"/><ref name="ATR-1960"/><ref name="usgs-1949">{{cite map |publisher=United States Geological Survey |title=Vancouver, 1949 |year=1949 |url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/topo/250k/txu-pclmaps-topo-us-vancouver-1949.jpg |scale=1:250,000 |format=JPG |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> The Yale Bridge was maintained by Clark and Cowlitz counties until the 1940s and had its timber approach spans replaced with steel in 1958 under maintenance of the [[Department of Highways (Washington)|Department of Highways]].<ref name="haer-bridge2"/> SR&nbsp;503 was established during the [[1964 highway renumbering (Washington)|1964 highway renumbering]] and codified in 1970 as the successor to SSH&nbsp;1U and part of SSH&nbsp;1S between Battle Ground and Woodland,<ref name="RCW"/> while the remaining portion of SSH&nbsp;1S between Mount Vista and Battle Ground became [[Washington State Route 502|SR&nbsp;502]].<ref name="sr">{{citation |last=Prahl |first=C. G. |title=Identification of State Highways |url=http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/NR/rdonlyres/6836215D-E301-43F3-895A-472BD2FDE86A/0/Identification.pdf |publisher=Washington State Highway Commission, Department of Highways |date=December 1, 1965 |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name="usgs-1967">{{cite map |publisher=United States Geological Survey |title=Vancouver, 1967 |year=1967 |url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/topo/250k/txu-pclmaps-topo-us-vancouver-1967.jpg |scale=1:250,000 |format=JPG |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> The highway in the Lewis River valley, between Woodland and the Yale Bridge, was closed following the [[1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens|May 18, 1980 eruption]] of [[Mount St. Helens]] and re-opened after the Yale Bridge was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in July 1982.<ref name="nrhp-bridge"/><ref name="sthelens-1980">{{citation |date=May 23, 1980 |title=State roads opening |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xIZUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MY8DAAAAIBAJ&dq=sr%20503%20st%20helens&pg=4965%2C4123510 |page=3 |work=[[Daily Record (Washington)|Ellensburg Daily Record]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> The [[Washington State Route 503 Spur|spur route]] of SR&nbsp;503 was added to the state highway system in 1991 as part of the original Lewis River Road between Yale and the Skamania county line in the [[Gifford Pinchot National Forest]].<ref name="RCW"/><ref name="law1991">{{citation |author=Washington State Legislature |title=Session Laws of the State of Washington |edition=1991 |series=Session Laws of the State of Washington |date=May 21, 1991 |accessdate=February 9, 2013 |url=http://apps.leg.wa.gov/billinfo/summary.aspx?year=1991&bill=5801 |publisher=Washington State Legislature |location=Olympia, Washington |chapter=Chapter 342: Engrossed Senate Bill 5801 - State Highway Routes -- Revisions To}}</ref> Between Orchards and [[Amboy, Washington|Amboy]], SR&nbsp;503 was designated as the "Lewisville Highway", serving historic [[Lewisville Park]].<ref name="wstc-bgh">{{citation |title=Resolution No. 692 |date=May 20, 2009 |url=http://www.wstc.wa.gov/Meetings/Resolutions/692.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Washington State Transportation Commission]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name="katu-bgh">{{citation |title=Two Battle Ground highways are being renamed |date=June 1, 2009 |url=http://www.katu.com/news/local/46671757.html |work=[[KATU]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref>

{{clear}}
==Spur route==
{{Infobox road small
|state=WA
|type=SR
|subtype=SPUR
|route=503
|location=[[Yale, Washington|Yale]]&ndash;[[Skamania County, Washington|Skamania]] county line
