|length_ref=<ref name="log"/>
|length_round=2
|formed=1991
|yr_ref=<ref name="RCW"/>
}}

SR&nbsp;503&nbsp;Spur, known locally as the [[Lewis River Road]], begins its {{convert|8.42|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} route at an intersection with SR&nbsp;503 east of [[Yale, Washington|Yale]] and north of the [[Yale Bridge]].<ref name="gnis-yale"/> The highway travels northeast along [[Yale Lake]] through a forested region of [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]], passing [[Yale Park]] and the community of [[Cougar, Washington|Cougar]].<ref name="gnis-yalelake"/><ref name="gnis-yalepark">{{citation |date=May 1, 1991 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Yale Park |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:852833827187748::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1529470 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gnis-cougar">{{citation |date=September 10, 1979 |title=Feature Detail Report for: Cougar |url=geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=132:3:852833827187748::NO:3:P3_FID,P3_TITLE:1518146 |work=Geographic Names Information System |publisher=United States Geological Survey |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> SR&nbsp;503&nbsp;Spur turns east at Beaver Bay Park and ends shortly thereafter at [[Forest Highway|Forest Route 90]] on the [[Skamania County, Washington|Skamania County]] line south of [[Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument]] and [[Gifford Pinchot National Forest]].<ref name="log"/><ref name="google-spur">{{google maps |title=State Route 503 Spur |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Lewis+River+Rd&daddr=Lewis+River+Rd&hl=en&ll=46.03058,-122.305405&spn=0.127522,0.338173&sll=46.055647,-122.245485&sspn=0.004013,0.010568&geocode=FWPcvQId5tu0-A%3BFcTAvgIdG622-A&mra=me&mrsp=1,0&sz=17&t=m&z=12 |link=no |accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="usda-map">{{citation |title=Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument |date=June 2012 |url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/fsbdev3_007073.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[United States Forest Service]], [[United States Department of Agriculture]] |accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> The Lewis River Road was part of [[State Road 15 (Washington 1909-1919)|State Road&nbsp;15]] from 1909 until 1919 and was re-established in 1991 as a spur route of SR&nbsp;503.<ref name="RCW"/><ref name="law1909"/><ref name="law1991"/> [[Washington State Department of Transportation|WSDOT]] conducted a series of surveys to measure traffic volume in terms of [[Annual average daily traffic|AADT]] and calculated that 650 to 1,300 vehicles per day used the spur route in 2011.<ref name="ATR"/>

